\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Patch Management and Remediation Timelines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Remediation Mandate
\series default
:
 System Administrators shall test and deploy security patches or implement compensating controls within the following strict timelines,
 measured from the date of vendor release or vulnerability discovery:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Critical Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 15 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
High Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 30 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Medium Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 60 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Low Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 90 days.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Flaw Remediation
\series default
:
 The Department shall identify,
 report,
 and correct information system flaws.
 Security-relevant software updates shall be installed automatically where feasible (e.g.,
 workstation OS updates).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Testing
\series default
:
 All patches shall be tested on a non-production subset of systems (e.g.,
 a "pilot group") prior to county-wide deployment to minimize operational disruption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Change Control
\series default
:
 Critical and High severity patches may be treated as Standard Changes (pre-authorized) if defined in the 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Emergency patching requiring immediate disruption shall follow the Emergency Change procedure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Unsupported Software (End-of-Life)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Prohibition
\series default
:
 The use of software or operating systems that are End-of-Life (EOL) or End-of-Support (EOS) by the vendor is prohibited on County networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Transition Plan
\series default
:
 The IT Director must approve a migration plan to replace or retire assets at least 90 days prior to their EOL date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exception
\series default
:
 If EOL software must remain in use for critical business functions,
 it shall be:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Covered by a formal Risk Acceptance Memo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Isolated from the general network and the Internet (air-gapped or strictly firewalled).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Blocked from accessing CJI.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Verification and Rescanning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Validation
\series default
:
 Remediation actions shall be verified through a follow-up vulnerability scan or manual verification within seven (7) days of patch deployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
False Positives
\series default
:
 Vulnerabilities identified as "False Positives" by System Administrators must be validated,
 documented with evidence,
 and marked as such in the scanning tool.
 False positive designations shall be reviewed annually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Reporting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Report
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall generate a Monthly Vulnerability Compliance Report for the IT Director.
 This report shall track:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Total open vulnerabilities by severity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Mean Time to Remediate (MTTR).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Percentage of assets compliant with patching timelines.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
List of assets with overdue patches.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Cloud and Third-Party Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Shared Responsibility
\series default
:
 For cloud-based systems (SaaS,
 IaaS,
 PaaS),
 the Assistant IT Director shall ensure the contract or Service Level Agreement (SLA) specifies the vendor's responsibility for patching and vulnerability scanning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor Assurance
\series default
:
 The Department shall review third-party security attestations (e.g.,
 SOC 2 Type II,
 FedRAMP authorization) annually to verify vendor vulnerability management practices comply with County standards.
\end_layout

